{{Unreferenced|date=June 2008}}
A '''timestamp''' is a sequence of characters, denoting the date and/or time at which a certain event occurred. This data is usually presented in a consistent format, allowing for easy comparison of two different records and tracking progress over time; the practice of recording timestamps in a consistent manner along with the actual data is called '''timestamping'''.

Timestamps are typically  used for [[Data logging|logging events]], in which case each event in a log is marked with a timestamp. In filesystems, timestamp may mean the stored date/time of creation or modification of a file.

Examples of timestamps:
 2005-10-30 T 10:45 [[UTC]]
 2007-11-09 T 11:20 [[UTC]] 
 Sat Jul 23 02:16:57 2005

==Standardization==
The [[International Organization for Standardization]] (ISO) has defined [[ISO 8601]] which standardizes timestamps.

==Uses:===
You can handle Timestamps with many languages such as C, Php, Javascript, etc. 
With Php, its used like this :
<source lang="php">
// Getting the actual timestamp
$Timestamp = time();

// Creating a fictual Timestamp (July the 5th 2002 at 05:41:12 PM)
$day = 5;
$month = 7;
$year = 2002;

$hour = 17;
$minute = 41;
$seconds = 12;

mktime($hour, $minute, $seconds, $month, $day, $year); //returns 1025883672
</source> 

==Other meanings==
{{wiktionary}}

'''Timestamp''' can also refer to:

* A [[time code]] (in networking or video technology)
* [[Unix time]], the number of seconds since 00:00:00 UTC on January 1, 1970
* [[ICMP Timestamp]]
* A [[Trusted timestamping|digitally signed timestamp]] whose signer [[wikt:vouch|vouches]] for the existence of the signed document or content at the time given as part of the [[digital signature]]
* The modification or access [[system time|time]] of a [[computer file|file]] or [[directory (file systems)|directory]] in a computer [[file system]] or [[database]]

